05432nam a22008175i 9781442628144DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20162007onc    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013950324  a97814426281447 a10.3138/97814426281442doi  a(DE-B1597)465555  a(OCoLC)944178748  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aDT191b.M67 2006eb 7aSOC0030002bisacsh04a306.9/0939/722200aMortuary Landscapes of North Africa /ced. by David Stone, Lea Stirling. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2016] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (270 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPhoenix Presocractic Series00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tList of Figures -- tPreface -- t1. Funerary Monuments and Mortuary Practices in the Landscapes of North Africa -- t2. Interculturality and the Punic Funerary World -- t3. Monuments on the Margins: Interpreting the First Millennium B.C.E. Rock-cut Tombs (Haouanet) of North Africa -- t4. The ‘Mausoleum Culture’ of Africa Proconsularis -- t5. The Koine of the Cupula in Roman North Africa and the Transition from Cremation to Inhumation -- t6. The African Way of Death: Burial Rituals beyond the Roman Empire -- t7. Changing Urban Landscapes: Burials in North African Cities from the Late Antique to Byzantine Periods -- t8. Peopling the Mortuary Landscape of North Africa: An Overview of the Human Osteological Evidence -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCemetery and landscape studies have been hallmarks of North African archaeology for more than one hundred years. Mortuary Landscapes of North Africa is the first book to combine these two fields by considering North African cemeteries within the context of their wider landscapes. This unique perspective allows for new interpretations of notions of identity, community, imperial influence, and sacred space. Based on a wealth of material research from current fieldwork, this collection of essays investigates how North African funerary monuments acted as regional boundaries, markers of identity and status, and barometers of cultural change. The essays cover a broad range in terms of space and time - from southern Libya to eastern Algeria, and from the seventh century BCE to the seventh century CE. A comprehensive introduction explains the importance of the 'landscape perspective' that these studies bring to North African funerary monuments, while individual case-studies address such topics as the African way of death among the Garamantes, the ritual reasons for the location of certain Early Christian tombs, Punic burials, Roman cupula tombs, and the effects of rapid state formation and imperial incorporation on tomb builders. Unique in both scope and perspective, this volume will prove invaluable to a cross-section of archaeological scholars.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBurialzAfrica, North. 0aSepulchral monumentszAfrica, North. 0aTombszAfrica, North. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Archaeology.2bisacsh1 aLeone, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacKinnon, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMattingly, David J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoore, Jennifer P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStirling, Lea , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aStirling, Lea M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStone, David L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStone, David, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aYounes, Habib Ben, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/